How much do you care about ‘accuracy’ in fantasy novels?
.
What I mean by this is, do you expect fantasy novels to adhere to the physical and technological rules of our world? For instance, would you be accepting of a medieval world where cannons and guns were invented already, or a world where people live in castles yet can fly around with planes?
.
I personally don’t mind overly much, as long as those differences / contradictions make sense. Even with cultures I don’t mind that much. I’m okay with inspired fantasy that don’t fully adhere to the corresponding country as long as the author isn’t harmfully misrepresenting that country out of ignorance or malice. Even with medicine, which is supposedly my area of expertise (?) I’m fine. For instance, the 100 is absolutely terrible, with wildly useless CPRs and NO concept of blood typing, but hey, I just wrinkle my nose and let it slide.
Hell, most novels depict people being banged on the head and blacking out and having NO consequences whatsoever, when in reality it could well be a concussion / intracranial hemorrhage, which isn’t something you just wake up and walk away from. But hey, I’m not gonna pick a fight with every book for this.
.
All the books featured in this pic are ones on my Immediate TBR. Seen any you like or are also contemplating reading? (Yeah I know it’s hard to see in the pic—check out the first comment for tags to see what those books are!)
.
Also I finished Lord of Shadows last night and nope. Not okay. I am not okay.
(And cause people have been asking: it’s not an arc, I just was blessed with an early copy. My best guess is that book shipments to Taiwan come once every 1-2 months and LoS came along with ACOWAR.)
